<article about="/us/blog/threat-insight/persistent-actor-targets-ledger-cryptocurrency-wallets" class="node--type--blog-post node--view-mode--full node node-blog-full _legacy_content _blog-full">
  



  <div class="breadcrumbs _legacy_element _breadcrumbs"><div class="nav-crumbs"><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog" class="breadcrum__item-link">Blog</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item"><a href="/us/blog/threat-insight" class="breadcrum__item-link">Threat Insight</a></div><div class="breadcrumb__item">
            Persistent Actor Targets Ledger Cryptocurrency Wallets          </div></div></div>

  <div class="blog-banner">
    <div class="blog-banner__image">      <picture>
                  <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=7Wh7o07v 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=tRSCk3yL 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=oUdDTL3k 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1920_750/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=7Wh7o07v 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1440px)" type="image/webp" width="1920" height="750"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_1024_400/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=tRSCk3yL 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 1024px)" type="image/webp" width="1024" height="400"/>
              <source srcset="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_375/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=oUdDTL3k 1x" media="screen and (min-width: 768px)" type="image/webp" width="768" height="375"/>
                  <img loading="lazy" src="/sites/default/files/styles/image_768_300/public/misc/austin-distel-EMPZ7yRZoGw-unsplash.jpg.webp?itok=Texx9XqN" width="768" height="300" alt="Cryptocurrency Wallets" typeof="foaf:Image" />

  </picture>


</div>
    <div class="blog-banner__gradient-overlay"></div>
    <div class="blog-banner__heading-wrap">
      
      


<h1 class="blog-banner__heading">
      <span>Persistent Actor Targets Ledger Cryptocurrency Wallets</span>

  </h1>

    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="blog-content">
    <div class="blog-content__sharethis sharethis_toolbox sharethis_32x32_style">
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_label sharethis__label">Share with your network!</div>
      <div class="blog-content__sharethis_buttons sharethis_buttons">
        <div class="sharethis-inline-share-buttons"></div>
        
<span class="addthis_button_subscribe at300b UNCONVERTED" title=Subscribe>
  <span class="at-icon-wrapper block-subscribe-button__trigger block-subscribe-button__addthis"></span>
</span>


      </div>
    </div>
        <div class="blog-content__metadata blog-content__metadata-author">
      <span class="blog-content__date">  <time datetime="2020-11-04T21:33:54Z">November 04, 2020</time>

</span>
        <span class="blog-content__author">
                The Proofpoint Threat Research Team
  
        </span>
    </div>
    <div class="node-full__body blog-content__body">  <p paraeid="{38310250-729f-4eda-922c-be518fae6392}{250}" paraid="1337222391">In July 2020, cryptocurrency wallet company Ledger&nbsp;revealed&nbsp;a&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ledger.com/addressing-the-july-2020-e-commerce-and-marketing-data-breach" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">breach</a>&nbsp;of&nbsp;9500 customers&nbsp;names and contact information.&nbsp;In their announcement, they caution users to be aware of <a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/sites/default/files/proofpoint-credential-phishing-ebook.pdf">credential phishing attempts</a> and state that they will never ask [users] for the 24 words of [their] recovery phrase.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{18}" paraid="1682957155">On October 25, 2020, Proofpoint researchers discovered several thousand messages claiming to be from Ledger&nbsp;with subjects like, Your Ledger Live client may be compromised and Your Ledger assets may be at risk.&nbsp;The messages dont appear to be targeted at any specific industry or geography.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<h2 paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{28}" paraid="1033623163">Lures&nbsp;<br>
<img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</h2>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{33}" paraid="1025884169"><em>Figure 1: Email lure claiming to be from Ledger&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{39}" paraid="1382309859">The messages claim that Ledger has experienced a breach and that recipients should assume their cryptocurrency assets are at risk of being stolen. The suggested remediation is to download the latest version of Ledger Live and set up a new PIN.&nbsp;In line with Ledgers real statement following the June breach, the message never suggests that the user will be asked to share their recovery phrase. Instead, at the bottom of the message,&nbsp;a&nbsp;button prompts the recipient to Download latest version of&nbsp;Ledger&nbsp;Live.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{69}" paraid="1059984647"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{69}" paraid="1059984647"><em>Figure 2:&nbsp;Additional email&nbsp;lure claiming to be from Ledger&nbsp;&nbsp;</em></p>

<h2 paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{80}" paraid="2066361188">Landing page and malicious files&nbsp;</h2>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{90}" paraid="1901014545">The button takes the user to a spoofed Ledger Live download page with links to malicious&nbsp;downloads for Windows, MacOS, and Linux.&nbsp;The fake download page is hosted at&nbsp;hxxps://xn--ledgr-9za[.]com/ledger-live/download/, and when&nbsp;punycode&nbsp;is rendered in a users browser, it&nbsp;appears extremely similar to the real download page&nbsp;URL:&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{128}" paraid="76807002"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;<br>
Figure 3: Malicious URL with&nbsp;punycode&nbsp;character&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{139}" paraid="1629743990"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;<br>
<em>Figure 4: Real Ledger Live download URL&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{146}" paraid="653549299">&nbsp;<br>
Beyond the URL, the&nbsp;landing page for the malicious download closely mirrors the legitimate Ledger page, appearing to offer downloads for a variety of desktop platforms and mobile. However, there is one notable change.<img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"><em>Figure&nbsp;5: Spoofed Ledger Live download page with links to malicious executables&nbsp;</em>&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{161}" paraid="1173604611">The spoofed version removes the warning to users to beware of fake Ledger Live applications, seen on the real page below.<img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"><em>Figure&nbsp;6: Real Ledger Live download page&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{174}" paraid="184771934">Upon clicking the download button on the spoofed page,&nbsp;the installer is downloaded to the users machine.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{184}" paraid="960743772">The fake installer and&nbsp;fake&nbsp;Ledger Live&nbsp;have the following digital signature:<img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{184}" paraid="960743772"><em>Figure&nbsp;7: Signature for the installer and&nbsp;spoofed Ledger Live downloads&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{205}" paraid="329136046">While&nbsp;Proofpoint researchers&nbsp;have not conducted&nbsp;a&nbsp;full analysis on the malware,&nbsp;at the very least&nbsp;the&nbsp;backdoored Ledger Live application&nbsp;is capable of stealing recovery phrases. The&nbsp;Ledger&nbsp;hardware wallets themselves are not targeted in this campaign, instead&nbsp;users&nbsp;may be tricked into revealing their recovery passphrase&nbsp;through <a href="https://www.proofpoint.com/us/corporate-blog/post/cybersecurity-101-what-social-engineering">social engineering</a>.&nbsp;A stolen recovery phrase may be used by an actor&nbsp;to&nbsp;generate&nbsp;a copy of the&nbsp;users&nbsp;private keys, allowing them to steal any digital currencies associated with those private keys.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{84bc320f-622b-4575-8cf0-acc8b56cb0c2}{253}" paraid="841259834">To achieve this, the&nbsp;threat&nbsp;actor&nbsp;modified the&nbsp;Ledger Live&nbsp;application&nbsp;to&nbsp;trick&nbsp;users into selecting the Restore device from Recovery phrase option&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;8). The legitimate Ledger Live application typically has two additional options&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;9)&nbsp;on the Get started with your Ledger device page: Set up as new device and Skip device setup,&nbsp;which were removed in the backdoored application.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{58}" paraid="1823876512"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{58}" paraid="1823876512"><em>Figure 8: Backdoored Ledger Live Get started with your Ledger device with removed options&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{73}" paraid="441381658"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{73}" paraid="441381658"><em>Figure 9: Legitimate Ledger Live Get started with your Ledger device page&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{84}" paraid="123937943">After selecting the&nbsp;Restore device from Recovery phrase and choosing a Ledger wallet, the backdoor applications next step is the Recovery phrase&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;10),&nbsp;which is&nbsp;normally the third step in the legitimate application (Figure&nbsp;11).&nbsp;If a&nbsp;user&nbsp;is tricked into&nbsp;providing their recovery phrase in this stage of the backdoored&nbsp;application,&nbsp;the phrase&nbsp;is&nbsp;sent to&nbsp;actor-controlled infrastructure where they may then freely steal any digital currencies associated with that phrase.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{84}" paraid="123937943"><img alt="backdoor" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="c081ebd2-24b8-4a12-951a-3c62da377bc1" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/figure10_backdoor_ledger_recovery.png" width="1546" height="1160" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{138}" paraid="245932955"><em>Figure 10:&nbsp;Backdoored Ledger Live Recovery phrase as second step&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{138}" paraid="245932955"><img alt="Live VPN" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="9f56d44a-6d13-4a50-9e1b-6fa1286a89cc" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/figure11_real_ledger_PIN.png" width="1528" height="1216" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{147}" paraid="1923119708"><em>Figure 11:&nbsp;Legitimate Ledger Live PIN as second step&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{156}" paraid="2014893071">To backdoor the application, the&nbsp;actor&nbsp;inserted malicious JavaScript code into renderer.bundle.js, which&nbsp;can be found in Ledger Lives&nbsp;<a href="https://www.electronjs.org/docs/tutorial/application-packaging" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">app.asar</a>&nbsp;file.&nbsp;<a href="https://github.com/LedgerHQ/ledger-live-desktop/releases/tag/v2.15.0" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">Version 2.15.0</a>&nbsp;of Ledger Live was likely used as the basis for the backdoored application, with the legitimate renderer.bundle.js consisting of 405,057 lines while the backdoored render.bundle.js&nbsp;consists&nbsp;of 411,736&nbsp;lines (6,679 additional).&nbsp;&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{3905b3d7-3fa6-436e-9fb7-dd536b2a12e2}{194}" paraid="1672682528">The malicious code modifies the number of options available on the Get started with your Ledger device page based on&nbsp;whether&nbsp;the installation has been registered with the attackers command and control (C2) server. This is accomplished&nbsp;first&nbsp;with a&nbsp;HTTP GET request to&nbsp;the C2 server&nbsp;and checks for the following response string: unregistered&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;12).&nbsp;If the server responds with unregistered then only the noDevice and restoreDevice options are displayed (Figure&nbsp;8), otherwise the full list of options is displayed (Figure&nbsp;9).&nbsp;This request is&nbsp;also&nbsp;sent at every onboarding check&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;13).&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{21}" paraid="1956360141"><img alt="backdoor" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="637bb297-7a84-48db-90ab-d0a120d7c58c" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/figure12_backdoor_GET.png" width="1544" height="622" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{21}" paraid="1956360141"><em>Figure 12: Backdoored Ledger Live GET request&nbsp;and response&nbsp;(dogcowbat[.]com)&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{44}" paraid="979903388"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{44}" paraid="979903388"><em>Figure 13:&nbsp;OnboardingOrElse&nbsp;in backdoored Ledger Live&nbsp;(loldevs[.]com)&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{61}" paraid="117642123">If a&nbsp;user&nbsp;is tricked into entering their recovery phrase, the malicious code will check each entered word against a hardcoded list of&nbsp;<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptocurrency_wallet" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">BIP-39</a>&nbsp;valid words. If the word is found in the list&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;14), then&nbsp;a&nbsp;malicious work() function is executed until enough words&nbsp;making up the completed mnemonic sentence&nbsp;have been entered.&nbsp;Once all the words have been entered then the full mnemonic sentence is sent to the&nbsp;actor&nbsp;controlled C2 via a HTTP POST request (Figure&nbsp;15).&nbsp;Once a recovery phrase has been stolen,&nbsp;the&nbsp;actor is&nbsp;free to generate&nbsp;a&nbsp;private key with that phrase and&nbsp;are&nbsp;then be able to transfer any associated digital currencies to their own wallet.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{138}" paraid="866673218"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{138}" paraid="866673218"><em>Figure 14:&nbsp;Hardcoded BIP-39 words in backdoored Ledger Live&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{147}" paraid="1620447787"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on"></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{147}" paraid="1620447787"><em>Figure 15: Backdoored Ledger Live POST request (dogcowbat[.]com)&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{158}" paraid="397087006">Sometime on or before October 31, 2020, the actor launched a new campaign that&nbsp;similarly attempts to trick their targets into revealing their recovery phrase. Instead of&nbsp;using&nbsp;a backdoored Ledger Live,&nbsp;however, this campaign is purely web-based.&nbsp;At the time of writing, this campaign has not been observed via email. The landing pages that redirect to a recovery phrase-stealing webpage were likely sent through&nbsp;<a href="https://www.reddit.com/r/ledgerwallet/comments/jmdcov/now_its_usaledgercom_hope_the_noobies_dont_fall/" rel="noreferrer noopener" target="_blank">SMS messages</a>.&nbsp;One recovery phrase-stealing website was hosted at the following&nbsp;punycode&nbsp;URL: hxxps://xn--ldgr-vvac[.]com/update/ (Figure&nbsp;16).&nbsp;Similar to the spoofed Ledger Live download page, the decoded text from the&nbsp;punycode&nbsp;domain was made to look like the official Ledger website (ledger[.]com):&nbsp;ldgr[.]com.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{158}" paraid="397087006"><img alt="wallet" data-entity-type="file" data-entity-uuid="7fcf2a2c-91f8-45ea-966e-7a9e7bef7f2d" src="/sites/default/files/inline-images/figure16.png" width="693" height="706" loading="lazy"></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{229}" paraid="1578580034"><em>Figure&nbsp;16: Fake Ledger Wallet landing page used to steal recovery phrases&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{c5eb476d-44da-463b-8f1f-5a09db247ae3}{239}" paraid="608349346">After selecting a wallet, the webpage&nbsp;navigates to a time locked page requesting the target to connect their device&nbsp;(Figure&nbsp;17). Regardless&nbsp;of whether&nbsp;a device is connected,&nbsp;the page will&nbsp;eventually&nbsp;unlock the Continue button.&nbsp;When clicked, the button&nbsp;presents a fake error message&nbsp;asking the target to select their recovery phrase length (Figure&nbsp;18).&nbsp;The final page asks for each word to be entered separately (Figure&nbsp;19), and after all the words are entered then they are sent via a POST request to the same server.&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{37}" paraid="1333329122"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{42}" paraid="800796954"><em>Figure&nbsp;17: Fake Connect your device page&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{52}" paraid="155910074"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{57}" paraid="1021442864"><em>Figure&nbsp;18:&nbsp;Recovery phrase length prompt&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{69}" paraid="424734296"><img src="data:image/png;base64," unselectable="on">&nbsp;</p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{74}" paraid="544554077"><em>Figure 19:&nbsp;Prompt to enter in each recovery phrase word separately&nbsp;</em></p>

<p paraeid="{5f26c7c9-5ecb-4dff-8ffe-99aff1ac9885}{86}" paraid="592943913">Cryptocurrency wallets and related services have long been&nbsp;attractive&nbsp;targets for&nbsp;threat actors, taking advantage of platforms that may not have the most robust security measures in place.&nbsp;In this case, the actor used well-crafted lures and landing pages&nbsp;attempting to&nbsp;convince the&nbsp;recipient&nbsp;to download&nbsp;a fake update&nbsp;or directly&nbsp;reveal&nbsp;their recovery phrase.&nbsp;The&nbsp;Ledger breach in June may have&nbsp;inadvertently&nbsp;added&nbsp;legitimacy to these messages, as&nbsp;its likely still fresh in the minds of Ledger users.&nbsp;</p>
